item.title: Volvo, Renault, CMA CGM to Produce Electric Vans
item.description: Volvo and Renault will launch a new company, which CMA CGM plans to join, with creation expected in early 2024, and which will operate under its own corporate identity and be based in France.

item.title: Euro, Sterling Look Vulnerable to Any Dollar Rebound
item.description: The euro and sterling edged lower and are vulnerable to further falls if the U.S. monthly jobs data sparks a dollar rebound back toward this week’s multimonth highs, ING said.

item.title: Oil Ticks Higher But Set for Sharp Weekly Loss
item.description: Oil prices ticked higher in early European trading, but were on course for a massive weekly loss, after rising gasoline inventories in the U.S. triggered a sell-off for both Brent and WTI.

item.title: Metals Mixed Amid Demand Headwinds
item.description: Base metals were mixed, while gold edged up in early London trading, with demand headwinds continuing to pressure prices.

item.title: German Manufacturing Orders Beat Expectations
item.description: New orders at German factories rose 3.9% in August, albeit far from fully recovering after plummeting orders in July, indicating a still-fragile environment in the country’s manufacturing sector.

item.title: Shell Production Volumes to Meet Targets
item.description: Shell expects to report production of 880,000-920,000 oil-equivalent barrels a day of integrated gas for the third quarter, and said it expected earnings to be boosted by stronger gas and chemical trading.

item.title: Italian BTP Spreads Seen More Likely to Widen Than to Narrow
item.description: A widening of the 10-year Italian BTP-German Bund yield spreads toward 220 basis points is more likely than a narrowing toward 180bps from the current 200bps level, but the speed of widening might slow, Citi Research said.

item.title: Nikkei Falls 0.3%, Dragged by Electronics, Energy Stocks
item.description: The Nikkei Stock Average closed 0.3% lower at 30994.67 as falls in electronics and energy stocks offset gains in utility and food stocks.

item.title: India Central Bank Holds Rate Steady as Inflation Moderates
item.description: The Reserve Bank of India kept its policy rate unchanged as domestic inflation has moderated.

item.title: South Korea Plans to Fine Google, Apple for Breaching Mobile Payment Rules
item.description: South Korea’s telecom regulator plans to fine Alphabet’s Google and Apple a total of $51 million for allegedly abusing their market dominance and breaching the country’s mobile-payment regulations.

item.title: Who Will Be the Next House Speaker? A Look at the Race So Far
item.description: The candidates will depend on personal connections as well as staking out positions on Republican priorities.

item.title: Why Blue Apron and HelloFresh Can't Keep Their Customers
item.description: HelloFresh, Blue Apron and other major meal kit companies struggle to retain customers. WSJ examines how these food delivery companies, big and small, are competing to find and keep customers in a saturated market with an uncertain future.

item.title: Tesla Cuts Prices of Model 3, Model Y Vehicles in U.S.
item.description: The carmaker cut prices of its Model 3 and Model Y vehicles in the U.S., its website showed.

item.title: China Is Becoming a No-Go Zone for Executives
item.description: Foreigners are thinking twice about business trips to the country after Beijing has barred some executives from leaving.

item.title: 'Our Nuts Are in Crisis': Brits Lament Autumn Chestnuts Are Too Soft for Battle
item.description: Storms blew chestnuts from trees unseasonably early, leaving many too mushy to use at the World Conker Championships on Sunday.

item.title: Monetarism Is Back. It Might Not Last.
item.description: Some on Wall Street predict bad times because of an unprecedented drop in the money supply.
